parts.text:
[Statement 1]: No studies were found that evaluated the effects of breeding bats in captivity to supplement wild populations affected by white-nose syndrome.
[Statement 2]: Eight studies on breeding bats in captivity found that the reproductive success of captive-born pups varied.
[Statement 3]: Eight studies on breeding bats in captivity found that the survival of captive-born pups varied.
[Statement 4]: In six studies, 6% to 100% of wild-caught female bats successfully reared young in captivity.
[Statement 5]: In two other studies, some bats born in captivity also reproduced.
[Statement 6]: Survival rates for captive-born pups ranged from 20% to 100% from 10 days to adulthood, as observed in seven studies.
[Statement 7]: In another study, two of five captive-born pups survived and were hand-reared.

key: _gemini-2-5-pro__What is the success rate of reintroducing captive-bred bats into areas affected by white-nose syndrome?

parts.text:
[Statement 1]: No studies were found that evaluated the effects on bat populations of training arborists and forestry operatives to identify potential bat roosts.
[Statement 2]: No studies were found that evaluated the effects on bat populations of protecting roost trees during forest operations.

key: _gemini-2-5-pro__Will training arborists to identify potential bat roosts (Action 1981) be more effective than protecting known roost trees during forest operations (Action 1982)?
